WEBVTT

00:02.073 --> 00:11.606
This is an interview with Mr. Billy Pete 
Huddleston by Dwayne Purvis on May the 6th at the

00:02.073 --> 00:11.606
Petroleum Engineering Building at Texas A&M. In 
the interest of accumulating knowledge, I am

00:12.367 --> 00:20.377
asking you to donate this tape to me or to the Texas 
A&M Oral History Collection in the University

00:12.367 --> 00:20.377
Archives. Is that all right with you? That will be 
fine. All right. Let's talk a little bit about your

00:24.082 --> 00:26.525
background. Were you born and raised? I was born in 
a small West Texas town of Ira Ann, I-R-A-A-N. It

00:36.462 --> 00:40.508
was named after Ira and Ann Yates. Ira Ann also 
happens to be about the center of the Yates oil

00:40.528 --> 00:59.637
field, which is one of the largest oil fields in the 
North American continent, and still has the well

00:40.528 --> 00:59.637
that tested at the highest flow rate that's ever 
been tested in the North American continent, over

00:40.528 --> 00:59.637
250,000 barrels per day. That's incredible. So 
you grew up around there a little? I grew up in the

01:03.014 --> 01:04.936
field itself. I was actually born in an oil field 
camp in what they call their nurse's quarters,

01:04.996 --> 01:18.653
delivered by an oil field lady that was called a 
midwife that delivered all the children in the

01:04.996 --> 01:18.653
camp. In fact, I've got a photograph of the 82 
children that she delivered in that one oil field

01:18.673 --> 01:25.101
camp. busy camp. Yeah, right. Then you went to A&M 
for your undergraduate? I graduated from RN High

01:30.876 --> 01:34.321
School in 1952. I came to A&M on a football 
scholarship and studied petroleum engineering.

01:41.070 --> 01:45.477
I took some additional courses and graduated in 
five years. I ended up with 180 hours, but it was all

01:45.537 --> 01:49.082
in undergraduate work. I was not doing any 
graduate work at all. I'd worked in the summers

01:52.346 --> 01:55.611
beginning when I was 12 years old and pulling 
units, which is oil field equipment. By the time I

01:59.924 --> 02:06.874
was 15, I'd graduated to working on rotary rigs, 
and so I worked as a roughneck until I graduated

01:59.924 --> 02:06.874
from A&M. And I worked myself up as a relief 
driller, which is the highest position that you

02:08.256 --> 02:17.409
could get on the last summer that I worked prior to 
graduation. What year did you graduate? I

02:20.453 --> 02:23.337
graduated from A&M in 1957. I was employed by 
Marathon Oil Company. I started in East Texas,

02:27.118 --> 02:32.504
went to Mississippi, North Louisiana, Arkansas. 
Someplace in there, I had a two-year leave of

02:34.086 --> 02:38.311
absence. I served in a fighter interceptor 
squadron with the Air Defense Command in the

02:38.332 --> 02:44.319
United States. I was stationed in Massachusetts 
on Cape Cod, later at an Air Force base in Roswell,

02:44.439 --> 02:53.290
New Mexico. I went back to Marathon. I worked for 
them at South Louisiana, Texas Gulf Coast, and

02:56.369 --> 03:04.106
South Texas. I resigned from Marathon in 1965. I 
was 30 years old and formed my own business. Farmed

03:11.883 --> 03:13.845
Huddleston Company. It's consulting petroleum 
engineers.

