26:41.420 --> 26:47.850
contracts have been set aside and court has just 
nullified many of them and said that you will sell

26:48.691 --> 27:16.386
your gas on the spot market at a lower price did the 
did the sellers sue oh yes there was billions and

26:48.691 --> 27:16.386
billions of dollars of litigation the producers 
that had long-term contracts early on won the

26:48.691 --> 27:16.386
lawsuits probably in the first year or so but after 
that they've consistently lost what was the

26:48.691 --> 27:16.386
result of that Well, the result of it, of course, is 
that it broke a lot of producers that had gone out

27:17.497 --> 27:29.455
and spent a lot of money drilling expensive wells 
in anticipation of selling their gas for $3. When

27:30.436 --> 27:41.332
the court sent their contract aside and they had to 
sell it for $1, $1.50, they could not pay their bank

27:30.436 --> 27:41.332
debt off that they'd incurred to drill the wells, 
and they went broke. The 80s saw a lot of buyouts and

27:41.352 --> 27:46.440
mergers. happen a lot in oil and gas? Yes, there was 
a tremendous consolidation in the 80s. Many major

27:54.107 --> 27:57.673
oil companies sold out. Marathon Oil Company sold 
out to U.S. Steel. Texas Oil and Gas sold out to U.S.

28:02.201 --> 28:04.926
Steel. Comico was taken over by DuPont. Gulf was 
taken over by Chevron. City service was taken over

28:13.488 --> 28:17.172
by Occidental. Would those have happened if gas 
had not been deregulated?

28:24.739 --> 28:25.219
Probably. It was inevitable. We had a lot of excess 
infrastructure in the petroleum industry, in the

28:27.341 --> 28:33.968
domestic industry. If you go back and look, you can 
see that oil production particularly has

28:33.988 --> 28:41.335
declined steadily. So there had to be some 
retrenchment. We simply had too much at the top,

28:44.840 --> 28:52.692
frankly, and maybe too many people at the bottom, 
too, and so this is what brought about the

28:44.840 --> 28:52.692
consolidations. And we're going to continue to 
have consolidations. Were the consolidations

28:55.096 --> 29:00.945
good for the industry?

29:00.965 --> 29:02.287
I would say they were necessary. If you lost your 
job, you know, you certainly didn't think it was

29:02.888 --> 29:10.900
good for the industry or good for anything, but 
there was just no question because the declining

29:11.133 --> 29:14.239
profitability, there had to be a consolidation. 
So in order to survive, to keep any type of

29:15.041 --> 29:20.571
profitability level, there had to be 
consolidation. And that probably would have

29:20.852 --> 29:24.218
happened even without deregulation. Yes. You 
said a lot of people lost their jobs during the

29:26.860 --> 29:30.125
restructuring? Oh gosh, 350,000 people. We've 
lost half of the industry since 1981. Was that

29:36.273 --> 29:38.516
because of restructuring or because of prices? Or 
were the two separate? Both. The prices continued

29:42.322 --> 29:44.645
to deteriorate. Production continued to 
decline. So obviously in order to keep some level

29:47.769 --> 29:56.682
of profitability, you had to have a whole lot less 
people, which is the single most expensive

29:47.769 --> 29:56.682
component in the production of oil and gas. I 
remember, back to the gas, which got me into that

29:58.113 --> 30:11.649
idea, I remember hearing that the pipelines were 
opened up and made available to every producer

29:58.113 --> 30:11.649
equally. That's correct. When did that happen? 
Well, actually, that was Order 636, and it just

30:15.253 --> 30:18.958
happened this last year. There's been a series of 
orders, but in effect, The whole structure of the

30:25.822 --> 30:41.783
gas pipeline industry, which is Enron, ANR, Texas 
Eastern, Panhandle Eastern, Florida Gas,

30:25.822 --> 30:41.783
Transwestern, El Paso, these are your major 
pipeline companies. They had served for many

30:41.803 --> 30:53.618
years prior to just last year's what we call 
merchant gas companies in that they went and

30:41.803 --> 30:53.618
signed up a lot of long-term contracts with lots of 
producers. They aggregated that gas, and then

30:54.374 --> 31:09.173
they turned around and made long-time sales 
contracts with a lot of major industries in a lot of

30:54.374 --> 31:09.173
major cities, Chicago, Detroit, New York, 
Philadelphia, Pittsburgh, and so on. With 636

31:09.193 --> 31:23.892
called the unbundling of services, the Federal 
Energy Regulatory Commission said that the gas

31:09.193 --> 31:23.892
companies could no longer serve in a merchant 
function, that the end users of gas could contact

31:24.158 --> 31:41.315
the producer or any gas sales and buy gas directly 
from them and the gas pipeline that was hooked up to

31:24.158 --> 31:41.315
those wells was obligated to transport that gas to 
the customer. Now they could charge a

31:41.895 --> 31:51.725
transportation fee but at that point we no longer 
had merchant gas companies and essentially

31:41.895 --> 31:51.725
you've had producers selling directly to end 
users now. So were the Were the merchant gas

31:55.394 --> 32:00.160
transporters held liable for violation of 
contract? Oh, yes. They lost early on when the

32:02.744 --> 32:15.861
Federal Energy Regulatory Commission first took 
the position that the end user, the customer, no

32:02.744 --> 32:15.861
longer had to satisfy their purchase contracts. 
They said, you're excused out of buying this gas,

32:15.882 --> 32:22.971
even though you've got 15 years left on it. The 
pipelines were not excused from their contracts

32:23.440 --> 32:28.428
from the producer. To buy. To buy. So there they had 
gone out and bought billions of dollars worth of

32:31.353 --> 32:40.006
gas under long-term contract, and they had no 
customer on the other end that was obligated to buy

32:31.353 --> 32:40.006
it. So did we lose a lot of gas transporters? We 
didn't lose. any gas transporters but they lost

32:45.901 --> 33:15.047
billions and billions of dollars columbia for 
example the major gas transmission line is in

32:45.901 --> 33:15.047
bankruptcy today transco came very close to 
bankruptcy the and the gas companies

32:45.901 --> 33:15.047
consistently lost their cases fighting the 
contracts in court with the producers in the early

32:45.901 --> 33:15.047
years in the last four or five years they've had a 
lot more success but they're still losing cases

32:45.901 --> 33:15.047
still losing cases so are these are Were they able 
to make a surcharge to the user to help pay for their

33:15.668 --> 33:21.978
indebtedness? No. They simply said the end user 
does not have to buy the gas anymore. They can buy it

33:27.306 --> 33:29.569
any place if they find it cheaper. But when the 
pipeline said, OK, we'll pass the second rule that

33:30.230 --> 33:41.648
lets us out of our contracts with the producer, the 
Federal Energy Regulatory Commission told them,

33:30.230 --> 33:41.648
that's your problem. So why were the gas 
transporters the one that took the hit? Well,

33:45.115 --> 33:46.737
nobody really knows. Federal Energy Regulatory 
Commission only addressed half of the problem and

33:47.358 --> 33:53.207
refused to address the other half of the problem. 
No understanding why? No. They just said, that's

33:55.931 --> 33:57.293
not our problem. Our problem is to protect the end 
user. And that's between the producer and the

34:01.079 --> 34:04.244
pipeline company. You'll just have to fight your 
problems out in court. How did the changes in

34:09.031 --> 34:13.738
bankruptcy law in the late 70s change our 
business?

34:18.359 --> 34:33.894
Probably the largest single change is they gave 
what we call in Chapter 11 presenting the debtor in

34:18.359 --> 34:33.894
possession a lot greater latitude than they had in 
previous years. For example, as companies began

34:34.895 --> 34:43.843
to go into bankruptcy, previous years they could 
be forced to sell their assets. And whatever they

34:43.963 --> 34:48.147
get for them, they give it to their creditors. In 
the late 70s, early 80s, Chapter 11 proceedings

34:48.987 --> 35:06.057
under the bankruptcy code would give the debtor in 
possession typically at least 18 months of

34:48.987 --> 35:06.057
continued operation before he had to satisfy any 
type of claims. At the end of 18 months, he had to

35:07.279 --> 35:13.510
come into court with what we'd call a plan of 
reorganization of saying, I'm going to pay off the

35:14.232 --> 35:18.159
secured creditors $0.25 on the dollars. The 
unsecured creditors, I'm going to give them $0.05

35:18.199 --> 35:24.170
on the dollar, and so on. So debtor in possession 
left the same management in the companies for much

35:24.190 --> 35:32.525
longer periods of time than it had previously. 
That was destructive to the industry? Oh, I don't

35:35.866 --> 35:38.250
know that it was so destructive. It just changed 
the way that you functioned in bankruptcy court.

35:43.097 --> 35:48.366
We didn't go through near as many liquidations 
after that particular change. I can't say that

35:48.646 --> 35:50.689
it's good or bad. How did the changes in the tax law 
in 1986 change the way we do business?

35:57.760 --> 36:03.409
And was 1986 the end of the 70% windfall tax? Yes, 
because when the price of oil went down, there was

36:03.997 --> 36:15.656
no oil being taxed above that level, so there was no 
need for a windfall profits tax, and it was phased

36:03.997 --> 36:15.656
out. Some of the things that have hurt, they phased 
out, maybe in the late 70s, early 80s, they phased

36:15.936 --> 36:26.213
out depletion allowance for all major oil 
companies. It had been 27.5% of gross income that

36:27.215 --> 36:31.101
was not taxed. It went to 15%, and then they took it 
to 0% for a major. Independence still had it. Then

36:39.414 --> 36:45.501
they put in preference tax items where all 
intangible drilling costs could not be deducted.

36:45.601 --> 36:48.144
It had to be capitalized.

36:49.185 --> 36:58.696
I don't think that the change in tax laws, it had an 
impact, a negative impact on the industry, but not

36:49.185 --> 36:58.696
an overwhelming impact. I mean, they could have 
lived with, if that was all that had been the

37:00.292 --> 37:02.836
problem. So the oil industry paid more taxes, 
especially the big oil companies paid more taxes?

37:08.725 --> 37:08.805
Yes. I mean, question, because they totally lost 
their depletion

37:08.865 --> 37:18.720
amounts. Have there been any debacles in foreign 
policy that have really screwed up our industry?

37:25.811 --> 37:26.692
It's hard to say. The accusation has been, and 
there may be some element of proof, that during

37:28.473 --> 37:40.765
Desert Storm, we were not really there, the 
accusation is, to protect Kuwait. Because

37:41.665 --> 37:50.594
Kuwait's got relatively few people, and there's a 
lot more injustices that have been done to people

37:41.665 --> 37:50.594
all over the world than there was in Kuwait. What we 
were really over there for was to protect our oil

37:51.234 --> 37:57.180
supply that was coming out of Saudi Arabia. I don't 
think that there's been any evidence to support

37:58.139 --> 38:16.643
it, but the allegation now from some corners is 
that Saudi made a deal to continue to produce at

37:58.139 --> 38:16.643
maximum rates since Desert Storm, since we sent 
our people over there really to protect their

37:58.139 --> 38:16.643
country. Them producing at maximum rate has 
depressed the price of oil dramatically, and that

38:18.445 --> 38:27.437
was their deal, is that they said, okay, if you'll 
come over here and and protect us. We'll pump oil at

38:29.436 --> 38:31.178
a maximum rate. The price of oil will stay way down. 
You're importing a lot of oil, and that would be

38:33.420 --> 38:36.583
good for the United States. It's very detrimental 
to the petroleum industry, but probably very

38:37.364 --> 38:43.230
favorable to the rest of the consumer.

38:46.373 --> 38:54.100
I heard, as recently as last summer, that OPEC had 
adopted a long-term strategy of keeping the price

38:46.373 --> 38:54.100
of oil about $20. so that alternative energy 
wouldn't develop and they could maintain a large

38:54.350 --> 39:01.621
energy market share for the long term. Are they 
abandoning that strategy now? Well, they

39:03.744 --> 39:05.787
certainly have on the short term. OPEC and Saudi is 
producing at a very high rate. They could run the

39:12.898 --> 39:17.805
price of oil back up to $20 a barrel if they'd shut 
back 5%. But in the past, Almost a year now, they

39:21.063 --> 39:22.826
have not done it. Price of oil has been as low as $12, 
$13 a barrel in the United States. Currently, the

39:28.575 --> 39:30.859
posted price is $17. The actual field price is 
probably about $15, $16. That's for West Texas?

39:36.848 --> 39:37.029
Yes. What's going to happen when Iraq comes online 
and then when the Soviet Union comes back online?

39:43.928 --> 39:46.091
Well, let's talk about Iraq first. If Iraq comes on 
and they can probably put as much as 3 million

39:46.131 --> 39:56.745
barrels a day, if nobody else cuts back, price will 
go to $10 a barrel.

39:57.246 --> 40:04.156
If they were to come back on and OPEC kept their 
production rate very high, price of oil will

39:57.246 --> 40:04.156
plummet. Soviet Union will not come back on. I've 
been in Russia for over two months. I've looked at

40:09.002 --> 40:11.826
hundreds and hundreds of wells Their production 
went from 12 million barrels down to 6.5 million

40:12.329 --> 40:16.113
barrels. Over what time? Over about a four-year, 
five-year period. The story that you read in the

40:21.259 --> 40:27.947
paper is that these wells have minor mechanical 
problems, and they just need a little help. And the

40:28.928 --> 40:35.856
fact is that those wells have fatal flaw problems, 
is that they've got poor quality pipe. Their

40:36.296 --> 40:38.539
cement jobs are almost nonexistent. The only way 
to fix those wells is to plug them and totally

40:39.329 --> 40:44.195
re-drill them. The Soviet Union, to get their 
production level back, probably needs a minimum

40:44.695 --> 40:53.185
of $50 billion of drilling activity. Billion? 
Billion. How much did you say we spent? We spent

40:56.449 --> 41:00.153
$160 billion over a six-year period. And the 
Soviet Union needs a minimum of $50 billion, and at

41:01.174 --> 41:06.400
this point, on any joint ventures formed over 
there, they've got a minimum of $6 a barrel tax on

41:07.375 --> 41:14.142
it. So their tax rate is so high that they're simply 
not economical to drill in Russia today. So

41:20.048 --> 41:23.592
they're asking American producers to produce at 
$6 a barrel? Well, to start with, the Americans in

41:23.692 --> 41:31.000
the joint ventures are required to put up 100% of 
the money. They only get half of the oil. Just to

41:34.190 --> 41:39.157
start with, you're selling oil on the Black Sea for 
$9 a barrel. You only get, I mean, for $18 a barrel,

41:40.499 --> 41:44.164
you only get half of it. That's nine. It costs

41:46.027 --> 41:55.640
$3 a barrel to transport it from Siberia, which is 
their major producing area, to the Black Sea. So

41:55.681 --> 41:56.942
that leaves you with six. Tax is $6 a barrel. That 
leaves you with nothing. And we haven't even

42:00.668 --> 42:03.792
talked about operating costs yet. So there's not a 
lot of people rushing over there? No. Soviet

42:07.911 --> 42:18.222
production is not going to go back to 10 to 12 
million barrels a day, in my opinion, in the

42:07.911 --> 42:18.222
foreseeable future. Should the federal 
government do something to help oil companies get

42:19.584 --> 42:26.631
in over there, or should they do something to keep 
oil companies out? Well, I don't know whether it

42:27.853 --> 42:32.918
should be the federal government's part. 
worldwide economics dictate what should be done.

42:36.666 --> 42:48.201
Obviously, if the government paves the way for big 
infusions of capital into the Soviet Union, that

42:36.666 --> 42:48.201
money is going to stay in the Soviet Union.

42:51.425 --> 42:58.855
The problem with investments in the Soviet Union 
is that we have not seen any type of proposal where

42:51.425 --> 42:58.855
you're going to bring capital out of Russia. 
Essentially, when you go over there and drill,

42:59.678 --> 43:11.090
then you're going to reinvest your cash flow into 
some type of Russia infrastructure, which is

42:59.678 --> 43:11.090
going to be refining transportation type of 
facilities. So in effect, you're exporting a lot

43:11.110 --> 43:22.642
of US capital and a lot of US jobs to Russia, which 
are going to be filled by Russians, not by

43:11.110 --> 43:22.642
Americans. There seems to be a movement in a lot of 
oil companies to produce abroad. Yes. And how does

43:30.037 --> 43:36.006
that affect U.S. jobs, and how does that affect 
U.S. tax revenue? Well, we obviously are

43:37.629 --> 43:43.037
exporting jobs and exporting taxes to foreign 
countries. It's just that simple. Because once

43:45.841 --> 43:48.966
you spend the money over there, they're going to be 
taxed over there. Those tax credits apply for U.S.

43:50.589 --> 43:53.072
taxes. The U.S. might get some tax dollars, but it 
would be greatly diminished from what we would if

43:59.298 --> 44:01.821
it were generated in the United States. But also 
those jobs are exported. When we go overseas and

44:03.703 --> 44:13.975
you go out location, you look at production 
facilities, at most you'll see 10% Americans.

44:14.235 --> 44:21.183
You're going to see 90% of the people that are 
working there are nationals, which is probably

44:14.235 --> 44:21.183
what they should be. But that means you just 
exported those jobs. You also export the support

44:23.927 --> 44:26.790
people, which is the dry cleaner, the grocery 
store, the filling station man. You export the

44:33.489 --> 44:37.315
whole community overseas when you go into this 
type of thing. What about equipment? Are we

44:38.196 --> 44:40.680
exporting steel jobs? Is the steel coming from 
somewhere else? No. Any country that is capable of

44:42.584 --> 44:51.598
producing steel or has ties to another company 
closer than they do to the United States will use

44:42.584 --> 44:51.598
steel from there. For example, when you go into 
Russia, you might bring in some steel from the

44:55.154 --> 44:59.220
United States. But sooner or later, there's going 
to be a deal. They'll have to get their steel up to

45:02.805 --> 45:04.908
specs. They're going to insist on furnishing the 
pipe themselves.

45:11.097 --> 45:13.780
They're going to do as much for themselves as they 
possibly can. What Russia wants from the United

45:14.822 --> 45:18.908
States is one thing, money. They don't want our 
technology. They don't want advice. They just

45:23.334 --> 45:24.115
want money. They want to set up their own company. 
That's correct. And you pay for it.

45:34.586 --> 45:38.892
So what does the industry look like for the next 
five years? Industry will continue. Domestic

45:43.098 --> 45:46.022
industry will continue to go through downsizing. 
We will lose probably in the neighborhood of eight

45:52.546 --> 46:21.287
percent to ten percent of our workforce each year 
the domestic budget will decline at the rate

45:52.546 --> 46:21.287
currently running about 20 billion dollars a year 
for production exploration it will decline also

45:52.546 --> 46:21.287
at about that same rate so we'll probably get down 
to a bedrock budget of around 10 billion dollars

45:52.546 --> 46:21.287
compared to the current 20 billion dollars We're 
essentially going to continue to go through

46:22.280 --> 46:26.106
restructuring. Major oil companies will 
continue to transfer oil properties by sales to

46:26.186 --> 46:35.920
mid-sized to smaller independent companies. 
Will those independents explore or will they just

46:35.941 --> 46:39.967
produce? No, they'll just produce out what we've 
got. There will be very little exploration. Do you

46:44.093 --> 46:45.775
expect the number of independents to grow? 
Probably.

46:50.512 --> 46:57.238
There is a size really that is a more efficient 
size. When you get too small, you don't have the

46:57.258 --> 46:59.900
staff capability. Probably the most efficient 
size of independent that is not going to explore is

46:59.920 --> 47:08.108
in the range of $50 to $150 million in assets. That 
means about how many people?

47:14.453 --> 47:19.658
Counting field people in the neighborhood of 50 to 
150 people. What

47:20.836 --> 47:26.155
about long term, the next 40 years?

